Lu and coworkers39 reported more pronounced performance of home-made edge-hydroxylated boron nitride (BNOH) in the ODH of propane and ethane to the corresponding olefins with high selectivity and negligible CO2 formation, on which high propane conversion (20.6%) and olefin selectivity (80.2% for C3 and 90.9% for C23) were achieved with considerably low CO2 formation (0.5%) (Fig. 2c). Meanwhile, feeding propylene and molecular oxygen did not consume propylene, demonstrating the suppression of its over-oxidation in the BNOH catalytic system. BNOH also exhibited olefin productivity of 6.8 golefin gcat1 h1, which was far higher than those of metal oxide catalysts, and remained stable for at least 300 h (Fig. 2d).
In the ODH of ethane on BNOH,42 the ethylene selectivity reached up to 95%, 90%, and 80% at the ethane conversion of 11%, 40%, and 63%, respectively, with only a negligible amount of CO2 (Fig. 3a). These results show that the BNOH catalyzed ODH is comparable to the industrialized ethane steam cracking process in view of their ethylene selectivity (85% at 60% ethane conversion for the latter), but wins over the latter considering the much lower reaction temperature and CO2 emission.79 The BNOH catalyst can also afford high ethylene productivity (9.1 gC2H4 gcat1 h1) with >90% selectivity by modulating the reaction conditions (Fig. 3b). The remarkable stability of the BNOH catalyst was evidenced by the operation for 200 h at 590 C (Fig. 3c). Such stable productivity far exceeded the critical value, 1 gC2H4 gcat1 h1, and demonstrated its potential application for industry.36
