By means of various advanced experimental characterization techniques and computational methods, the determining role of edge BOH groups was identified unambiguously,39,42 which represented a distinct understanding with that reported.38 The comparative study40 on the catalytic activity of several boron-containing compounds (B4C, Ti2B, NiB, CoxB, HfB2, and WB) and elemental B in ODH also confirmed the importance of BO sites and showed that the absence of nitrogen sites did not eliminate the catalytic activity of boron-containing compounds. The knowledge on the responsible species in the h-BN catalytic systems has since then been evolving, and it is now a consensus38,39,42,78,8083 that oxygenated boron species dictate the performance of the boron-based catalysts.
The suppression of over-oxidation of alkanes on h-BN was also demonstrated by the ODH reactions of n-butane and isobutane,84 in which the main side products were observed to be C2 and C3 olefins rather than COx. In contrast, the main side product was COx in the Cr-based,85,86 V-based,87 and P modified CNT50 catalytic systems at similar alkane conversion levels. The total selectivity of all formed olefins (ethylene, propylene, butylene, and isobutylene) on the h-BN catalyst was over 85% at 10% alkane conversion. This also showed that h-BN may be used in n-butane oxidative cracking to produce ethylene and propylene by decreasing the presence of O2 to shift the dominant product distribution from butylenes (oxidative dehydrogenation products) to propylene and ethylene (cracking products), which may be further enhanced at elevated reaction temperature with high selectivity for propylene (43.9%) and ethylene (24.2%), and the catalytic system remained stable for over 100 h with low total COx selectivity (1.2%).88
Hexagonal boron nitride is known with the low presence of defects. Accordingly, an option to further optimize its catalytic performance would be to increase the number of active sites. High surface area boron nitride nanosheets synthesized by the reaction of boric acid with urea were reported to show high activity for ODH of ethane with nearly 100% selectivity for ethylene at 10% conversion of ethane, which changed to 60% if raising the ethane conversion to 78% during which the catalytic system remained stable for at least 400 h at 575 C.41 When using dicyanamide to substitute for urea in the preparation for high surface area boron nitride,43 its enhanced catalytic performance was maintained in the ODH of propane in view of the 53% propylene selectivity and 18% ethylene selectivity at a 52% propane conversion. However, the operation time of this catalytic system was measured to be only about 5 h, owing to the oxidation of surface BN bonds in the oxidative atmosphere, which may be improved by the addition of ammonia to more than 100 h. Ball-milled h-BN can expose more edge sites with significantly increased surface area, leading to a significant improvement in view of the ethylene selectivity (92%) at 10% ethane conversion in ODH of ethane compared to pristine h-BN (42%).89
The third way to increase the number of active sites is via nanostructural engineering by assembling 2D h-BN into a 3D spherical superstructure. This catalyst afforded a selectivity of 78% for propylene and 10% for ethylene at the propane conversion of 20% in the ODH of propane and operated for 100 h at 490 C, and increasing the temperature to 510 C resulted in high conversion of propane of 58% but bifurcated olefin selectivity (48% for propylene and 21% for ethylene).47 This study also showed that this morphology lowered the apparent activation energy to 175.3 kJ mol1, implicating that lower energy channels were favored on this catalyst.
The preparation of a boron nitride wash-coated monolithic catalyst49 offered an applicable way to improve, besides the olefin selectivity, the heat and mass transfer which is vital for industrialization owing to the intrinsic feature of high exothermicity of the ODH reaction that could produce hotspots and thus subsequent negative consequences in the olefin selectivity and safety issues. This h-BN wash-coated cordierite monolithic catalyst was fabricated by chemical vapor deposition using boric acid and urea as precursors, and exhibited 82.1% propylene selectivity with only 3.7% CO and no detected CO2 at 16.8% propane conversion in the ODH of propane with high gas hourly space velocity (GHSV, 576000 mL gBN1 h1) (Fig. 4a). The well-developed straight-channel and short diffusive pathway of the thin wash-coated h-BN layer guaranteed the mass transfer process at high GHSV, and achieved a high propylene productivity of 18.6 gC3H6 gBN1 h1, both of which are critical indicators for the potential industrial implementation of ODH.49
