The presence of hotspots in the catalyst bed is a typical phenomenon in the ODH of light alkanes owing to its highly exothermic nature, which can significantly accelerate the undesired over-oxidation of olefins, leading to a low selectivity to olefins. It is a consensus that the catalyst design is one of the two key components in an industrial implementation, with another one the reactor engineering, and an ideal strategy is determined by their optimal synergy.9 Boron nitride materials are known with high thermal conductivity (33 W m1 K1), and thus are ideal choices to remove quickly the heat generated in ODH reactions, which is crucial to the industrialization of the ODH protocol. A recent computational fluid dynamics (CFD) simulation compared the hotspot and the temperature profiles in the fixed-bed reactor in the ODH of propane using h-BN and VOx/γ-Al2O3 as catalysts, respectively,90 and showed that the temperature of the catalyst bed increased by less than 1 C in the h-BN catalyst bed which was much smaller than that in the VOx/γ-Al2O3 catalyst bed (8 C) at a similar propane conversion (25%) with a micro-tubular reactor of 6 mm in diameter. The high thermal conductivity of an h-BN catalyst could maintain isothermal operation in such a micro-tubular reactor at even up to 590 C with a higher propane conversion of 45%. In contrast, a hotspot of >5 C temperature gradient was inevitable in the VOx/γ-Al2O3 catalyst bed even at the relatively low temperature of 520 C. In an industrially relevant reactor with an inner diameter of 60 mm, the h-BN catalyst bed maintained a uniform temperature profile (a temperature gradient as small as 1.5 C), while the VOx/γ-Al2O3 catalyst bed suffered from a temperature gradient of 47 C (Fig. 4b). These results suggest that the superior thermal conductivity the h-BN catalyst favors its industrial practice in ODH of light alkanes conducted in a fixed-bed reactor.
The investigation of the influence of reactor parameters on the ODH of propane using the h-BN catalyst showed91 that there was little transport limitation, and the use of SiC as an inert catalyst diluent may promote the catalysis significantly. This work attributed this to the contribution of the surface-initiated gas phase radical reactions, which is different from the opinion in the CFD simulation90 that emphasized the known high thermal conductivity of the catalyst. In this work, the authors reported a volcano-like dependence of the propane consumption rate on the mass of h-BN. This may be the consequence of multiple reasons, e.g. the contribution of gas-phase radical chemistry that did not rely on the quantity of the catalyst, the forming and encapsulation of the catalyst, and other issues, which remain to be clarified.
2.2.2 Silicon boride Silicon borides have a number of phases with a stoichiometric ratio of B:Si ranging from 3 to 6 with complicated morphologies varied from homogeneity to heterogeneity.9294 According to a crystallographic study, the unit cell of SiB6 contains 289 atoms with 281 of them building up interconnected icosahedra (18) and icosihexahedra (4).95 Silicon borides are generally synthesized by melting a certain proportion of elemental silicon and boron at high temperature and pressure, and adjusting the temperature and the ratio of B/Si may result in their various phases.
Silicon borides are widely used as substrates in the synthesis of ceramic composite96 and borosilicate glass materials,97 or as an additive in the modification of carbon fibre/lithium aluminosilicate composites.98 They are also used as an antioxidant coating material taking advantage of the facile formation of an oxide film on their surface, showing their good oxidation resistance at high temperatures.99,100
Though rarely used in catalysis, their rich boron sites and good oxidation resistance endow them as potential catalysts to promote ODH of light alkanes. In a recent study, oxygenated silicon borides were prepared with SiB6 as the main phases and remarkable catalytic performance was observed in ODH of light alkanes including ethane (95.8% C2 at 29% ethane conversion, and 90% C2 at 50% conversion), propane (82.2% C3 at 19% propane conversion, and 88.7% C23 at 31% propane conversion) and isobutane (77.1% C4 and 96.4% C24 at 6% isobutane conversion, and 90.9% C24 at 15.6% isobutane conversion),45 showing superior performance in resisting over-oxidation of olefins at high conversion (Fig. 5). In addition, the light olefin productivity was up to 1.22.6 golefins gcat1 h1, and the silicon boride catalyst in the ODH of propane remained stable for more than 100 h.45 Note that most silicon boride materials have relatively low specific surface areas, and the synthesis of silicon boride with high specific surface may be an effective way to improve its catalytic activity.
