2.2.4.2 Boron oxide embedded in zeolites Zeolites are crystalline aluminosilicate materials with three-dimensional network containing channels and cavities of molecular dimensions, and the presence of Al in tetrahedra makes the framework negatively charged.139 In their protonated form, they may be used for acid-catalyzed refining of biomass and crude oil.140 New types of zeolite may be created by means of the so-called isomorphous substitution, e.g. high silica zeolites141 and borosilicate zeolites,142,143 including RUT,144,145 Beta,143 MFI,146,147 MEL,148 MWW,149 CHA,150 FAU,151,152 and UTL.153 Compared with aluminosilicate, borosilicate zeolites exhibit lower acidity owing to the weaker BO bond that was protonated.154 This weaker BO bond can be broken upon dehydration and rebuilt upon hydration, enabling the boron atoms to be tetra-, tri-coordinated or both in the framework.143,155,156 Further hydrolysis leads to the leakage of boron from the framework in the form of boric acid, leaving silanol nests155 which can be used for isomorphous substitution of heteroatoms157,158 or generating mesopores.159
The weak Brnsted acid site of borosilicate zeolites has been confirmed vital to the improvement of selectivity in some reactions, e.g. xylene isomerization,160 olefin oligomerization,161 Beckmann rearrangement of cyclohexanone oxime162,163 and methanol conversion to hydrocarbons.164,165 In methanol to propylene (MTP) reaction, pure B-MFI zeolites were found to be insufficient to activate methanol,166 and those with weak acidity could catalyze methylation which is vital to olefin formation.165 Studies revealed that the acidity of the catalysts was a dominant factor in determining the key step of methanol converting to propylene in the process of olefin formation.167,168 However, strong acidity was shown to be a double-sided sword, e.g. for ZSM-5 zeolite, and may promote the conversion of methanol on one hand, while accelerating the side reaction on the other hand and lead to the deactivation of the catalysts. It was shown that the strong acidic sites of ZSM-5 zeolite may be modified by doping boron to give rise to weak Brnsted acidity, which prevented the formation of ethylene oligomers and resulted in higher propylene selectivity in methanol conversion.142,164,165
Isomorphous substitution of tri- or tetravalent metal atoms (Al, Ti, Fe and V) by borosilicate zeolites is a good route in the production of some new zeolites that need expensive organic structure directing agents (OSDAs), long crystallization time or co-presence of dopant.157,158,169 For example, the Ti-MWW with high crystallinity was successfully synthesized based on the ERB-1 (MWW topology) where the boron acid acted as a structure-supporting agent.170 Furthermore, taking advantage of the high propensity of boron to hydrolyze, its presence benefits the fabrication of mesoporous zeolite, and may increase the mesopore volume by 46%.159
Recently, layered borosilicate zeolite (ERB-1, MWW structure) with defective trigonal boron species was reported as a highly active and selective catalyst for the ODH of propane to take advantage of their specific morphology inherent with large internal surface areas, micropore structure and high thermal stability.171 In these synthesized zeolites, the boron species were classified into five types according to solid-state 11B MAS NMR, i.e. framework trigonal B(OSi)xOH3x(x=1,2), B(OSi)3, tetrahedral B(OH)2(OSi)2, B(OSi)4 and aggregated terminal BOH species (Fig. 8a and b). The layered borosilicate zeolites showed comparable catalytic activity with h-BN in the ODH of propane, and increasing boron content resulted in higher propane conversion with the propane conversion of 5.6%, 9.3% and 30.6% corresponding to the boron content of 1.54 wt.% (BZEO-1), 2.48 wt.% (BZEO-2) and 4.88 wt.% (BZEO-3), respectively (Fig. 8c), among which the BZEO-2 was determined as the optimal recipe which afforded a C3 selectivity of 80.4% and C23 of 91.6% at 15.6% conversion of propane (Fig. 8d). Owing to the large surface area and micropore structure, the catalyst was stable for 20 h under ODH conditions without structural collapse (Fig. 8e). These recipes had similar active sites in view of their similar apparent activation energies in the ODH of propane (Fig. 8f). In ethane ODH, the layered borosilicate zeolite exhibits 30.6% ethylene yield at 37.6% ethane conversion. This catalyst provided a new platform to investigate the influence of the microporous structure on the transport of gaseous species and the construction of a specific chemical environment for boron in the ODH of light alkanes in order to achieve optimal performance.
