A latter density functional theory (DFT) study202 tried to compromise the two hypotheses of Hermans and Lu groups in the O2 activation in the ODH of propane on h-BN, in which the reactivities of armchair, boron-atom-terminated zigzag (zig-B), and nitride-atom-terminated zigzag (zig-N) edges of h-BN were compared and proposed that O2 was more likely to be activated at the zig-B edge. This study stressed the important role of the zig-zag edge of h-BN in the ODH of propane, which was consistent with the opinion in earlier work,39 but remained to be improved for a fair comparison of the various potential reactive sites by using an equivalent reference point.
The governing role of oxygenated boron species in the ODH of light alkanes has been extended to explain the activity of other boron-based materials, e.g. B4C, Ti2B, NiB, elemental boron,40 and silicon boride203 In these catalytic systems, resembling surface species and kinetic behaviors to h-BN in the ODH reaction were observed. These results implicated that the boron-based catalysts have similar active phases of oxygenated species (BO or BOH) on the catalyst surfaces.
This was directly demonstrated in a work that used boron oxides supported on silicon oxide as the catalyst that explicitly correlated the catalytic activity to the percentages of oxygenated species. To better understand the structure of the active sites, Lu and coworkers synthesized mesoporous silica-supported boron oxide catalysts (B2O3/SBA-15) and identified four B species by using the 11B NMR technique,44 two of which on the upfield side (B(3a) and B(3B) in Fig. 7a) were considered as the responsible species for the activity by analyzing their variations before and after the ODHP test. With the aid of DFT calculations, these species were characterized as the boroxol ring and the tricoordinated planar BO3/2 species, respectively.
The activity of tricoordinated boron species and the inertness of tetracoordinated species were confirmed in further studies of the boronsilicate zeolite catalytic system.46,171 These studies also showed that clustered distribution of tricoordinated boron species is necessary. In the study using a layered borosilicate zeolite (ERB-1, an MWW borosilicate zeolite) with defective trigonal boron species as the catalyst,171 abundant presence of defective trigonal boron species (OBOH and B(OSi)xOH3x(x=1,2) species) was reported based on the data of FT-IR and 11B MAS NMR, and proposed to be responsible for the activity of propane ODH. These types of species (Fig. 7c) were also proposed to present in the amorphous silica supported oxidized boron catalytic system during the ODH of propane captured by IR, Raman, and solid-state NMR spectroscopy (Fig. 11c, d and e).138 When boron was incorporated into the zeolite framework as isolated BO3 species (equivalent as B(3c) in ref. 44 or isolated BO3 in ref. 138), its activity to catalyze the ODHP reaction was lost.46 This result gives a new perspective to the active sites and implicated that their accumulation at the surface was a prerequisite to promote the ODH reaction. Note that these incorporated species were considered inactive in the ODH of propane in an earlier work.44
2.4.2 Reaction mechanisms Characterization of the kinetics of the ODH reactions via advanced experimental techniques provided abundant information to understand the underlying mechanism. The combination of in situ FTIR and online MS showed39 that the signals of OH groups of the BNOH catalyst remained unchanged in the absence of O2 in the feed gas, but diminished in the presence of O2, implicating that the co-presence of alkane and O2 is a prerequisite in the ODH of light alkanes catalyzed by boron-based catalysts. The diminished signals of an OH group could be recovered under a steam atmosphere (Fig. 12a), which, together with the isotope labelling experiment, showed the direct involvement of water in the replenish of the BOH groups. These spectroscopic data and kinetic experiments indicated that the hydrogen and oxygen atoms of OH(D) groups were involved in the reaction process (Fig. 12b and c), which also lent support to a later computational study of the mechanism that considered the breakage of the BO(H) bond during the reaction.204 The kinetic analysis suggested that the reaction order of O2 was 0.5, implicating the dissociation of O2 in the ODH reaction. The reaction order of C3H8 was calculated to be 2, and the kinetic isotope effects of CH cleavage were measured to be 1.4 for primary hydrogen abstraction and 1.5 for secondary hydrogen abstraction. The results suggested that activation of propane determined the total reaction rate, based on which a reaction mechanism was proposed78,81 (Fig. 12d) initiated by the reaction of BOH groups with O2 to generate active species that may further dehydrogenate propane to produce propylene and water, and recover BOH groups.
