3.2 Identification of active sites
Carbon materials have complex surface compositions and structures, and are rich in functional groups, defects and edge sites, making it difficult to establish a clear structureactivity relationship regarding their catalytic performance in ODH of alkanes. In earlier studies, oxygen containing carbonaceous species were proposed to be responsible for their activity in ethylbenzene (EB) ODH.209,228,229 This was verified by characterization of the surface oxygenated groups using temperature-programmed desorption (TPD) and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) techniques230 and thermal and chemical treatments of carbonaceous materials,231 from which a linear relationship between the EB conversion rates and the surface concentration of carbonyl/quinone groups based on TPD results (Fig. 14a) was established.231
