Since the edge sites, defect sites and other oxygenated groups (hydroxyl, carboxylic acid, and anhydride groups) of carbon may convert to carbonyl groups in the aerobic environment at increased temperature, it is not straightforward to identify their specific roles and contributions.52,232 To avoid this ambiguity, Qi et al. proposed a chemical titration method (ex situ and in situ) using an analogous organic molecule, i.e. phenylhydrazine, to selectively passivate the specific oxygenated functional groups (ketonic or quinone carbonyl groups) (Fig. 14b). This method provided an intrinsic catalytic activity value (turnover frequency, TOF, based on ketonic carbonyl groups) among various nanocarbon catalysts (GO materials, CNTs and OLCs), revealing that ketonic or quinone carbonyl groups were identical active sites of nanocarbons for an EB ODH reaction.233,234 Moreover, certain polymers were also synthesized to serve as model catalysts, only containing the quinone carbonyl groups, to provide indirect evidence for identifying active sites.235,236 The important role of quinone groups or ketonic groups was also demonstrated in view of their presence on the spent CNFs and OLCs after the EB ODH212,213 and the sharp increase of the ratio of XPS signal strength I(COH)/I(CO) (from 0.72 to 1.87) was observed after switching off the oxygen in the ODH of n-butane (Fig. 14c).50
Besides the studies that supported the significant role of carbonyl/quinone groups in ODH of hydrocarbon,225,235239 there were also opinions52,220,221 that proposed the edge sites and defects of the carbon catalysts as the active sites rather than the quinone-type groups. DFT study on the role of the surface oxygen content, edge sites and defects of a few-layer graphene model suggested that the exposed edges of carbon materials were essential and the dicarbonyls at the zigzag edges and quinones at armchair edges might be responsible for high activity (Fig. 14d).223,224
By means of first-principles calculations, epoxy groups,240 ketone, diketone and quinone groups241 have been evaluated as potential active sites in the ODH of propane. These studies proposed the CH bond breaking of propane as the rate-determining step, and showed the site-dependence of the activity which emphasized the importance of surface modification.240 The progress of the computational studies on the ODH of light alkanes catalyzed by nanocarbons has been reviewed and close cooperation between experimental and theoretical studies is expected to further promote the development of ODH reaction systems.242
As mentioned above, the carbonyl/quinone groups could be considered as active sites and a plausible mechanism was proposed that carbonyl/quinone groups could abstract hydrogen atoms from the CH bonds of alkane to form olefin, then gas phase oxygen molecules or dissociated oxygen species react with abstracted hydrogen atoms to form water, involving the regeneration of active sites. A recent review of oxidative dehydrogenation on nanocarbon catalysts from an in situ experimental account stressed that the behavior of O2 or dissociated oxygenated species was still not clear enough to establish a detailed catalytic mechanism of the ODH process from the molecular or atomic level, and more in situ characterizations were required to capture the intermediate species during the activation process of oxygen molecules.53
3.3 Selectivity control of olefins
Generally, the selectivity of styrene is close to 90% in EB ODH reaction over carbonaceous catalysts probably due to the stable π-conjugated structure of styrene which enables it to survive from being further oxidized. Such a conjugated structure is absent in olefins produced in the ODH of light alkanes, and their oxidation produces unwanted COx product under the severe reaction conditions. The ODH of alkanes may be considered to include competitive reactions (Scheme 3) from alkanes to olefins (rate constant of k1) and to COx (k3), and the over-oxidation of alkenes to COx (k2),221,243 in which k1 was usually less than k2 and a maximum olefin yield (35%) could be reached when k1 was equal to k2.243
Scheme 3 The competitive pathways in the ODH of light alkanes.
Typically, the surface oxygen species of nanocarbons are classified into electrophilic (superoxide O2, peroxide O22) and nucleophilic (O2) types.50 Electrophilic oxygen species are electron-deficient and they prefer to attack the electron-rich CC bonds in olefins, which could increase the k2 value, causing the rupture of the carbon skeleton and lowering the selectivity of olefins. In contrast, electron-rich nucleophilic oxygen species, like carbonyl/quinone groups, are selective to convert alkanes to olefins and inactive to catalyze the combustion of olefins during an ODH system. Therefore, limiting the generation of electrophilic oxygen species and maintaining the amount of nucleophilic oxygen species can achieve the target for higher selectivity to olefins.
Heteroatomic (boron, nitrogen and phosphorus elements) doping and modification are often used to modulate the electron density, acidity or basicity and oxygen groups on the surface of nanocarbons. Doping boron atoms into CNTs resulted in an increase of propylene at the cost of decreased reaction rate in the ODH of propane,244 showing that the presence of boron weakened the reactivity of the CNTs. The authors observed active oxygen exchange in dynamic isotope oxygen tracer experiments when using oCNT, which was significantly suppressed when using boron doped oCNT catalysts (Fig. 15a), and concluded that the incorporation of boron could inhibit the generation of peroxide and superoxide species that were responsible for both higher rate of propane conversion and its over-oxidation in the undoped oCNT catalytic system, by which the selectivity of propylene was improved dissociation of molecule oxygen and/or cover the combustion sites to increase the propylene selectivity. Similar phenomena were observed in the borate-modified nanodiamond catalytic system when used for the ODH of propane.219
