The doping of electron-rich nitrogen element may generate multiple nitrogen species, among which the graphitic nitrogen was shown to play determining roles in the ODH of propane to promote the catalytic activity by reducing the apparent activation energy from 117 kJ mol1 (N-free CNT) to 111 (0.47% surface N) or 106 (0.57%) or 98 (1.44%) kJ mol1 when doped with N, and speeding up the activation of oxygen (Fig. 15b).245 This was confirmed in density functional theory (DFT) calculations which showed that the graphitic nitrogen could lower the barrier to the cleavage of the first CH bond.246
Upon the modification by phosphate,218 nanodiamond behaved similarly as in the B- and N-doped nanodiamond catalytic systems discussed above in their ability to suppress the formation of COx and improve propylene selectivity in the ODH of propane owing to the same reason, i.e. phosphate could react with the phenol groups on the nanodiamond surface and selectively block the defect sites to inhibit the production of electrophilic oxygen species (Fig. 15c).
These above-mentioned nanodiamond catalysts have their surfaces covered by sp2 carbon species. For fresh diamond which was composed of sp3 carbon atoms, fragmented products rather than a dehydrogenated one were formed in the initial stage according to an earlier comparative study of the catalytic transformation of ethylbenzene by sp3-hybridized ultra-dispersed diamond (UDD) and onion-like carbon (OLC), respectively, with benzene formed in the initial stage on the former and styrene formed on the latter.247 The analogous phase-transformation process of carbon from the sp3 to the sp2 hybridization state was also identified in the ODH of n-butane, and the authors proposed that the curved and graphitic surface might be beneficial to generate quinone groups rather than electrophilic oxygenated species, e.g. carboxylic or their anhydrides, resulting in enhanced olefin selectivity.216 The relationship between the quantity of electrophilic oxygen and side reaction rate was revealed using the iodometric titration method in ODH of n-butane, and the selectivity of C4 olefins may be improved by elimination of electrophilic oxygenated species through chemical reduction (LiAlH4 or Grignard reagents) or annealing in nitrogen.248,249
5 Comparison of the ODH catalysts
5.1 Catalytic performance
Table 2 shows the catalytic performance of typical metal-free and metal-based catalysts in ODH reactions. Metal-free carbon-based catalysts usually have lower catalytic activity than metal oxide catalysts, as demonstrated by the lower alkane conversion over the former than over the latter at similar reaction temperature (Table 2), which was attributed to the electronic properties of the center metal ion in the latter. In the ODH of propane, at low reaction temperature (400 C) highly crystalline CNTs and CNFs exhibited relatively high selectivity to propylene (4060%) at low propane conversion level (<5%). CNTs modified with boron or phosphorus oxide could enhance the oxidation resistance at a higher temperature (500 C) with the propylene selectivity maintained (40%) at the 20% conversion level. However, one deficiency that impedes the application of carbon-based catalytic systems is the low productivity of olefins which is always below 1 golefin gcat1 h1, making it hardly profitable for industrialization.
